metadata.name: DIGITAL DISOBEDIENCE #267
metadata.description:
As artists, we believe it is our duty to use our skills to comment on the state of the world and the pressing issues facing humanity. Through our art, we aim to pre-empt the future and explore the potential consequences of our current actions. We use symmetry as a visual metaphor for the balance we must strive for in society, particularly in regards to human rights and the treatment of marginalized groups. In the age of technology and AI advancements, it is more important than ever to consider the impact these developments may have on our world and the diverse individuals and communities that inhabit it. Our work serves as a reminder that we must take responsibility for our actions and work towards creating a more just and equitable future for all.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

metadata.name: Echoes of Enough #42
metadata.description:
"Echoes of Enough" is a collection that explores self-worth, acceptance, and validation. The collection presents a visual representation of the struggles, doubts, and triumphs of recognizing our own value. Each piece delves into different aspects of ourselves and how they contribute to this feeling.

The seemingly chaotic yet orderly arrangement of the shapes in this collection reflects the tumultuous nature of the human experience. It speaks to the push and pull of self-doubt and the struggle to acknowledge one's own worth, while the raw and unrefined nature of the collection reflects the brutal reality of the human experience.

A hidden harmony beneath the surface represents the truth that we are all enough, just as we are. The collection invites the viewer to look within and acknowledge their own struggles and triumphs and to find comfort in the realization that the feeling of being enough is always present, like an echo that lingers. 

It is a reminder that we are enough, just as we are.



The artwork is fully created in javascript with the p5js library. 
The ideal viewing resolution is 1000x1000, and the artwork can be scaled to any size/resolution. The grain effect will fade slightly for higher resolutions.

metadata.name: Livro #29
metadata.description:
A messy book is a well-read book, a sign of knowledge acquired. It's easy to spot a book that has been loved and used frequently. The pages are bent and creased, the spine is worn, and notes are scribbled in the margins. These imperfections are not a sign of neglect or carelessness, but rather an evidence of a book that has been fully engaged with and understood.
A book that is kept in pristine condition may look nice on a shelf, but it is also a sign that it has not been read as much, or not as deeply. A well-read book is an indication of a curious and active mind, always seeking to learn and grow. So, don't be afraid to let your books get a little messy, it's a sign that you're gaining knowledge and expanding your understanding of the world around you.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love <3

[S] to save as image

metadata.name: The Artifact #64
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Modificador de eventos #234
metadata.description:
Inspired by order and entropy cellular. 

Events that modify our trajectory often go unnoticed in our time. these events that arise in the course of our lives alter the trajectory and purpose of our lives, these events are beyond our control, beyond expectations and standards. The results of these trajectories are individually unique, the experiences of what has already been covered and the curiosity of what will be found, is what moves this perpetual autonomous game in its random trajectory. The overall behavior of the system is determined by the set of rules and modular functions.

I recommend running perpetual animation and resolution adaptive livecode in fullscream mode and using headphones, click anywhere on the running animation to listen.

livecode performed in hydra.ojack.xyz
ambient music recorded in vcvrack

- press 's' to save a frame from livecode tragectory

metadata.name: Badgirs City #151
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: lilium #7
metadata.description:
lilium is a remix of my piece for day 9 of genuary 2023, prompt "Plants". it uses a series of force-directed graph layouts to produce a bouquet of flowers. inspired by Jared Tarbell's Happy Place.

press "c" to capture a screenshot at the current resolution. if you'd like a screenshot at a particular resolution, you can press "r" and a prompt will appear that will let you select a fixed resolution. you can either provide a single number like "1080" or a series of two numbers like "1080x2160". you can also provide a fixed resolution in the url with the "?resolution=..."

metadata.name: terrains #198
metadata.description:
A generative set of imaginary landscapes.

Terrains continues a study of topographic media translations that began with Plastic Landscapes (2016) and our Field Guide to Martian Landscapes (2017). While the Field Guide focused on analyzing topographies of another planet, interpreted through telescopic imaging and software translation, this project focuses on the procedural generation of nonexistent landscapes. These landscapes are generated through a complex manipulation of perlin noise, a recurring algorithm used in videogames, film VFX, and generative art since the 1980s that resembles natural geological formations. By no means new, this tradition is part of a lineage of digital visualization projects focused on reproducing nature through algorithmic means. Our algorithm generates sequential bands of noise mapped on an X-Y plane, rendered in an oblique architectural projection, a techniques that comes from technical drawing conventions. This perspective produces a layering effect that flattens the terrain in an architectural way. Neither realistic nor completely abstract, the system plays with projection, entropy, and constraints to produce a collection of imaginary terrains sited on the Tezos blockchain.

We must also credit all who have explored this field of work: Ken Perlin, James M. Bardeen, Stephen Schmitt, Paul Bourke, Joseph Claghorn, Amit Patel, Inigo Quilez, Matt DesLauriers, and many many more...

Press "s" to download PNG.
Press "r" to redraw and shift stripes.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2023

metadata.name: amongst the straight and narrow #43
metadata.description:
This project continues my exploration of attempting to simulate drawing with markers, this time on top of a more textured fabric-like surface. The marks themselves can range from highly ordered to highly disordered, with various intermediate states.

---

So let us wander far,
Amongst the straight and narrow.
For it is in the detours,
That we find our souls' marrow.
